1
00:00:01,700 --> 00:00:04,950
<i>Kazu will accept me.</i>

2
00:00:06,350 --> 00:00:09,290
<i>I believe in him wholeheartedly, but...</i>

3
00:00:09,290 --> 00:00:11,050
<i>I get scared.</i>

4
00:00:12,570 --> 00:00:18,370
<i>Kazu, where do your true feelings lie?</i>

5
00:00:38,010 --> 00:00:39,970
Why?

6
00:00:59,090 --> 00:01:01,070
How is Sayaka?

7
00:01:12,650 --> 00:01:13,930
Here.

8
00:01:22,160 --> 00:01:24,630
Do you know what caused this?

9
00:01:28,050 --> 00:01:29,980
Not in the slightest.

10
00:01:32,840 --> 00:01:35,020
Why would she...

11
00:01:37,780 --> 00:01:41,050
I've been working hard for her sake.

12
00:01:41,050 --> 00:01:44,810
Is the reason you've kept in touch
with Chie Hashimoto,

13
00:01:45,480 --> 00:01:48,010
- also for Sayaka's sake?
- Huh?

14
00:01:49,180 --> 00:01:52,460
How did you... Did I ever mention that?

15
00:01:52,460 --> 00:01:54,960
<i>You're free to stay.</i>

16
00:01:57,390 --> 00:02:00,480
I've been talking to her about Sayaka.
[Chie: I enjoyed our chat the other day!]

17
00:02:01,080 --> 00:02:04,320
Chie is someone I can trust.

18
00:02:04,320 --> 00:02:07,040
She's been a great person to confide in.

19
00:02:07,040 --> 00:02:10,240
Seems like she had another agenda.

20
00:02:16,580 --> 00:02:21,750
<i>I happened to witness Chie and Airi</i>

21
00:02:21,750 --> 00:02:24,580
<i>on my way back from a shoot the other night.</i>

22
00:02:24,580 --> 00:02:28,680
<i>Thinking I could find another lead,
I decided to follow them.</i>

23
00:02:33,800 --> 00:02:35,950
<i>Long time no see!</i>

24
00:02:35,950 --> 00:02:37,880
- <i>So glad to see you're doing well.</i>
- Sayaka?

25
00:02:37,880 --> 00:02:40,350
That dress...

26
00:02:40,350 --> 00:02:42,600
So that's who she went to see.

27
00:02:42,600 --> 00:02:44,580
This is where things get complicated.

28
00:02:44,580 --> 00:02:48,040
<i>We wanted to ask you about Kazuomi.</i>

29
00:02:48,040 --> 00:02:52,460
You've never had any doubts about him?

30
00:02:52,460 --> 00:02:56,480
Kazuomi invited me out
while you were bedridden.

31
00:02:56,480 --> 00:02:58,210
<i>He said he wanted to talk.</i>

32
00:02:58,210 --> 00:02:59,230
What?

33
00:02:59,230 --> 00:03:04,410
He brought me to his place, held my hand,

34
00:03:05,110 --> 00:03:07,030
and even tried to kiss me.

35
00:03:07,030 --> 00:03:08,520
What?

36
00:03:08,520 --> 00:03:11,390
You're the one who wanted to read my palm.

37
00:03:11,390 --> 00:03:15,080
<i>He calls me to ask for "advice",</i>

38
00:03:15,080 --> 00:03:18,290
- <i>and complains about you.</i>
- Unbelievable.

39
00:03:20,560 --> 00:03:22,580
<i>Sayaka, I'm just worried about you.</i>

40
00:03:22,580 --> 00:03:27,540
<i>I want you to be happy.</i>

41
00:03:27,540 --> 00:03:29,850
<i>I really didn't want to say this, but...</i>

42
00:03:29,850 --> 00:03:34,430
I'm going to be blunt for your sake, okay?

43
00:03:35,870 --> 00:03:40,360
I think you should leave him.

44
00:03:40,360 --> 00:03:41,240
What?

45
00:03:41,240 --> 00:03:44,420
<i>That man's a cheater.
You're better off without him!</i>

46
00:03:48,860 --> 00:03:50,870
Me?

47
00:03:52,740 --> 00:03:54,410
A cheater?

48
00:03:55,450 --> 00:04:02,010
This is the person you've "trusted".

49
00:04:05,760 --> 00:04:08,540
She's the worst.

50
00:04:10,740 --> 00:04:12,400
What is with this woman?

51
00:04:12,400 --> 00:04:14,380
Chie Hashimoto can't stand being inferior.

52
00:04:15,220 --> 00:04:21,050
She especially seems to compare
her happiness to Sayaka's.

53
00:04:21,050 --> 00:04:22,540
In other words?

54
00:04:22,540 --> 00:04:29,550
She hoped to drag Sayaka out of marriage,
and back down to her level.

55
00:04:39,010 --> 00:04:41,640
I thought she was a good person.

56
00:04:43,590 --> 00:04:46,240
I never thought she'd be such a villain.

57
00:04:46,240 --> 00:04:51,170
You make that sort of judgement often.

58
00:04:51,170 --> 00:04:55,040
"They're good", "they're bad".

59
00:04:55,040 --> 00:04:59,730
But your evaluation changes often.

60
00:05:00,510 --> 00:05:02,410
Well, yeah.

61
00:05:03,460 --> 00:05:05,350
That's on people for changing.

62
00:05:05,350 --> 00:05:07,230
Is it really?

63
00:05:08,770 --> 00:05:11,990
You've interpreted both the "good" and "bad"

64
00:05:13,330 --> 00:05:17,250
in ways that would justify your actions.

65
00:05:19,890 --> 00:05:27,070
Even your own "good intentions"
can be misconstrued by Sayaka.

66
00:05:29,780 --> 00:05:32,440
You had met Chie Hashimoto in secrecy,

67
00:05:32,440 --> 00:05:35,580
while Sayaka was bedridden in the hospital.

68
00:05:35,580 --> 00:05:38,460
But that was because...

69
00:05:38,460 --> 00:05:45,040
<i>Sayaka then sees her husband
receive an intimate text from her friend.</i>

70
00:05:45,040 --> 00:05:47,010
I went to ask her about Sayaka.

71
00:05:47,010 --> 00:05:52,160
<i>Her husband begins returning home late.</i>

72
00:05:52,160 --> 00:05:56,950
How do you think she would interpret
this situation?

73
00:05:56,950 --> 00:06:00,860
Well, when you put it like that...

74
00:06:07,790 --> 00:06:10,890
You're an earnest man, Hayashida.

75
00:06:11,840 --> 00:06:18,050
But being earnest and naive
are two sides of the same coin.

76
00:06:19,840 --> 00:06:22,780
Good people. Bad people.

77
00:06:23,370 --> 00:06:29,720
You can't judge a person's true nature
if you only have two extremes.

78
00:06:30,830 --> 00:06:32,120
A person's true nature...

79
00:06:32,120 --> 00:06:35,740
If you only see things on a surface level,

80
00:06:36,850 --> 00:06:40,680
you'll eventually make
an irredeemable mistake.

81
00:06:40,680 --> 00:06:46,760
Don't you realize your actions till now

82
00:06:46,760 --> 00:06:50,860
have caused Sayaka an immense amount of pain?

83
00:06:56,170 --> 00:07:02,530
Sayaka was driven to suicide because...

84
00:07:07,410 --> 00:07:10,060
<i>Everything I've done was for Sayaka's sake.</i>

85
00:07:11,370 --> 00:07:17,200
<i>And yet... How am I supposed to face her now?</i>

86
00:07:38,870 --> 00:07:40,680
You're awake.

87
00:07:46,210 --> 00:07:48,950
I went and spoke to the doctor.

88
00:07:51,600 --> 00:07:54,940
They said you'll be discharged tomorrow.

89
00:07:56,780 --> 00:07:58,620
Kazu.

90
00:08:00,750 --> 00:08:02,980
You must be angry.

91
00:08:04,850 --> 00:08:06,840
I made a rash decision.

92
00:08:15,440 --> 00:08:17,220
I'm not angry.

93
00:08:19,640 --> 00:08:23,600
Was there anything you wanted from the store?

94
00:08:56,600 --> 00:08:58,080
Kazuomi?

95
00:09:00,130 --> 00:09:01,850
Hey, Kazuomi.

96
00:09:05,400 --> 00:09:07,750
Kazuomi.

97
00:09:07,750 --> 00:09:09,520
Kazuomi.

98
00:09:10,830 --> 00:09:16,040
I'm sorry I ran my mouth about your wedding.

99
00:09:19,170 --> 00:09:21,060
It's fine.

100
00:09:23,650 --> 00:09:25,530
It's not fine.

101
00:09:27,310 --> 00:09:30,410
This was supposed to be
a big moment for you two.

102
00:09:31,580 --> 00:09:37,580
And I totally rained on your parade.

103
00:09:38,550 --> 00:09:42,120
I'm really sorry about what I did.

104
00:09:43,690 --> 00:09:45,720
Let's put that behind us already.

105
00:09:50,940 --> 00:09:54,720
Why're you here on a weekday anyway?

106
00:09:54,720 --> 00:09:56,600
Are you feeling ill?

107
00:09:57,730 --> 00:10:01,410
No. My mother wasn't feeling too well.

108
00:10:04,260 --> 00:10:06,530
Is she okay?

109
00:10:06,530 --> 00:10:09,460
Yeah. Why're you here?

110
00:10:09,460 --> 00:10:10,450
[Makoto Sugiura: Ryokusei Pharmaceutical]

111
00:10:10,450 --> 00:10:12,470
I'm here on business.

112
00:10:14,660 --> 00:10:18,910
<i>Do you know a doctor,
or someone who's well versed in medicines?</i>

113
00:10:18,910 --> 00:10:24,240
<i>They could help us identify
this ulcer-triggering drug.</i>

114
00:10:24,240 --> 00:10:25,550
What?

115
00:10:26,280 --> 00:10:30,300
Are there any drugs
that can affect your stomach?

116
00:10:30,300 --> 00:10:31,850
That's a broad question.

117
00:10:31,850 --> 00:10:35,230
What about a drug that triggers an ulcer?

118
00:10:35,230 --> 00:10:39,150
I mean, it can be a potential side effect.

119
00:10:39,150 --> 00:10:41,900
What about something
that triggers the effect instantly?

120
00:10:41,900 --> 00:10:44,220
A sudden ulcer, huh?

121
00:10:45,230 --> 00:10:49,820
I can't think of anything
that specifically targets the stomach.

122
00:10:50,710 --> 00:10:51,930
Why ask?

123
00:10:51,930 --> 00:10:53,980
I was just curious.

124
00:10:55,710 --> 00:10:58,840
Then what about a drug
that turns blue when dissolved?

125
00:11:00,900 --> 00:11:03,270
It's a question that's been on my mind.

126
00:11:03,270 --> 00:11:04,970
Because, you know.

127
00:11:05,640 --> 00:11:07,310
I was curious.

128
00:11:08,110 --> 00:11:13,970
There is a medicine
that turns water blue when dissolved.

129
00:11:15,920 --> 00:11:17,770
It's a type of sleeping pill.

130
00:11:18,480 --> 00:11:20,450
A sleeping pill?

131
00:11:21,620 --> 00:11:26,270
I've never heard of one
that changes the color of water.

132
00:11:26,270 --> 00:11:29,140
It was a recent invention.

133
00:11:30,810 --> 00:11:35,430
You know, with the rise of people
using sleeping pills for no good.

134
00:11:36,120 --> 00:11:42,010
So people can instantly tell
if their drink has been spiked.

135
00:11:42,970 --> 00:11:45,070
Bingo.

136
00:11:46,030 --> 00:11:47,700
Is that why...

137
00:11:47,700 --> 00:11:50,970
<i>The culprit mixed it into her blue champagne?</i>

138
00:11:50,970 --> 00:11:54,330
Not all sleeping pills
have that effect, though.

139
00:11:58,700 --> 00:12:01,790
Say, are you free after this?

140
00:12:01,790 --> 00:12:03,180
Huh?

141
00:12:03,180 --> 00:12:05,020
Let me treat you to a drink or two.

142
00:12:05,020 --> 00:12:09,220
I want to make it up to you somehow.

143
00:12:14,030 --> 00:12:16,210
- Evening.
- Welcome.

144
00:12:17,590 --> 00:12:18,680
Could I get the usual?

145
00:12:18,680 --> 00:12:20,110
Of course.

146
00:12:20,110 --> 00:12:20,940
I'll have a whisky.

147
00:12:20,940 --> 00:12:22,710
Coming right up.

148
00:12:22,710 --> 00:12:25,900
Here. Cheers.

149
00:12:25,900 --> 00:12:30,250
<i>If Sayaka was only put to sleep,</i>

150
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:33,400
<i>does that mean the culprit
had no intent on killing her?</i>

151
00:12:37,870 --> 00:12:40,130
<i>But then why...</i>

152
00:12:40,130 --> 00:12:43,790
You were asking about pills
because of the wedding, right?

153
00:12:43,790 --> 00:12:45,150
What?

154
00:12:46,200 --> 00:12:48,550
You suck at making excuses.

155
00:12:51,510 --> 00:12:55,050
So Sayaka was drugged.

156
00:12:56,800 --> 00:13:01,000
Don't worry, I promise I won't tell a soul.

157
00:13:01,890 --> 00:13:08,730
But I've never heard of a sleeping pill
that'd cause an ulcer.

158
00:13:10,200 --> 00:13:12,010
<i>If that's true...</i>

159
00:13:12,010 --> 00:13:13,500
<i>Sayaka?</i>

160
00:13:13,500 --> 00:13:15,240
<i>Then why did she choke out blood?</i>

161
00:13:15,240 --> 00:13:17,030
- <i>Sayaka!</i>
- <i>Sayaka!</i>

162
00:13:17,030 --> 00:13:21,750
<i>Was it the stress and anxiety
that came from playing the violin?</i>

163
00:13:25,100 --> 00:13:31,940
She was already drowsy
from whatever she was drugged with.

164
00:13:31,940 --> 00:13:33,910
Did her added stress cause the ulcer?

165
00:13:35,880 --> 00:13:37,380
What?

166
00:13:42,980 --> 00:13:49,190
I still can't believe the bride herself
wrecked her own wedding.

167
00:13:50,150 --> 00:13:53,210
The gal's a bundle of misfortune, I tell you.

168
00:13:57,200 --> 00:13:59,210
Bundle of misfortune?

169
00:14:00,460 --> 00:14:05,000
And here I thought she'd be happy with you.

170
00:14:06,240 --> 00:14:08,650
I can already see her breaking down again.

171
00:14:10,260 --> 00:14:12,770
Does Sayaka know about the drugging?

172
00:14:14,520 --> 00:14:16,220
Why are you acting so familiar with her?

173
00:14:19,240 --> 00:14:22,110
Am I?

174
00:14:22,890 --> 00:14:25,330
Sorry, blame it on the alcohol.

175
00:14:25,330 --> 00:14:28,820
What do you mean breaking down, "again"?

176
00:14:29,900 --> 00:14:35,840
She's talked to me about her episodes before.

177
00:14:35,840 --> 00:14:41,200
I thought Sayaka was a friend of a friend.

178
00:14:42,680 --> 00:14:46,140
My bad. Didn't mean to fuel the flame.

179
00:14:46,140 --> 00:14:48,290
Just forget it, yeah?

180
00:14:48,290 --> 00:14:50,750
That's not happening.

181
00:14:52,970 --> 00:14:57,770
What aren't you telling me?

182
00:14:57,770 --> 00:14:59,790
Nothing, nothing.

183
00:14:59,790 --> 00:15:03,200
This is how you behave whenever you lie.

184
00:15:04,870 --> 00:15:07,410
What was your relationship to Sayaka?

185
00:15:13,250 --> 00:15:15,860
Look me in the eyes, damn it.

186
00:15:21,260 --> 00:15:23,350
Yeesh, you're such a buzzkill.

187
00:15:32,070 --> 00:15:36,070
I was dating her.

188
00:15:41,120 --> 00:15:42,700
When?

189
00:15:46,650 --> 00:15:51,660
We broke up before I introduced you to her.

190
00:15:57,700 --> 00:15:59,660
Wait, but weren't you...

191
00:16:02,500 --> 00:16:04,780
Yeah, I was already dating my wife.

192
00:16:04,780 --> 00:16:06,300
Then you were...

193
00:16:06,300 --> 00:16:09,470
Two-timing them? Yeah.

194
00:16:11,170 --> 00:16:14,870
What's with that look, man?

195
00:16:14,870 --> 00:16:17,650
It's not that unheard of.

196
00:16:18,470 --> 00:16:23,580
<i>That's why I called Sayaka
a "friend of a friend".</i>

197
00:16:23,580 --> 00:16:26,070
<i>Sorry for lying.</i>

198
00:16:26,070 --> 00:16:31,050
<i>She's actually a girl I met on a dating app.</i>

199
00:16:31,050 --> 00:16:33,940
A dating app famous for hookups and flings.

200
00:16:37,590 --> 00:16:43,910
<i>But you wouldn't have given Sayaka
the time of day if I told you that.</i>

201
00:16:43,910 --> 00:16:47,060
<i>So I kept some details under wraps.</i>

202
00:16:47,060 --> 00:16:52,040
<i>I wanted you two to tie the knot, after all.</i>

203
00:16:55,150 --> 00:17:01,300
If I'm being honest,
Sayaka and I were only friends with benefits.

204
00:17:01,300 --> 00:17:03,270
Friends with benefits.

205
00:17:03,270 --> 00:17:06,520
Hope that shared experience
doesn't bother you.

206
00:17:06,520 --> 00:17:07,790
Shared experience.

207
00:17:07,790 --> 00:17:11,570
Eventually, my actual girlfriend got pregnant,

208
00:17:11,570 --> 00:17:13,780
so I took responsibility and married her.

209
00:17:13,780 --> 00:17:18,570
Sayaka and I would break up,
and that'd be that.

210
00:17:19,440 --> 00:17:24,160
Except, she became insane
when I asked to end things.

211
00:17:24,160 --> 00:17:28,290
She'd send me letters
when I blocked her number,

212
00:17:28,290 --> 00:17:30,680
and followed me everywhere. Creepy, huh?

213
00:17:30,680 --> 00:17:32,770
Your infidelity is the real issue here.

214
00:17:32,770 --> 00:17:36,330
Hey, woah. Sayaka's not any better than me.

215
00:17:36,330 --> 00:17:41,390
You know how her mother is, right?

216
00:17:41,390 --> 00:17:46,050
Maybe she needed to rebel to feel in control,

217
00:17:46,050 --> 00:17:51,170
but Sayaka really went wild
when she left the nest.

218
00:17:55,480 --> 00:17:58,870
I bet I wasn't her only "friend".

219
00:18:02,330 --> 00:18:06,880
Of course, I pitied her home situation.

220
00:18:06,880 --> 00:18:10,460
But her persistence
wasn't making it any easier on me.

221
00:18:12,370 --> 00:18:18,700
And that's when you came into the picture.

222
00:18:26,420 --> 00:18:29,470
You pushed a woman onto me,

223
00:18:33,850 --> 00:18:35,370
because you didn't need her anymore?

224
00:18:35,370 --> 00:18:40,040
Hey, I'm the reason you're married at all.

225
00:18:40,040 --> 00:18:41,910
No need to be so harsh, yeah?

226
00:18:41,910 --> 00:18:47,820
Besides, I set you two up...

227
00:18:48,940 --> 00:18:51,780
For Sayaka's sake, too.

228
00:18:52,480 --> 00:18:54,400
How?

229
00:18:54,400 --> 00:18:56,170
How does this benefit Sayaka at all?

230
00:18:56,170 --> 00:19:02,320
I felt bad leaving her single
while I got married.

231
00:19:03,320 --> 00:19:05,290
Huh?

232
00:19:05,290 --> 00:19:08,680
I know I ended up dumping her.

233
00:19:10,060 --> 00:19:15,370
But I did like her quite a bit.

234
00:19:16,750 --> 00:19:18,310
Quite a bit?

235
00:19:18,310 --> 00:19:21,090
Yeah, I cherished her.

236
00:19:21,090 --> 00:19:24,140
I felt responsible when we broke up.

237
00:19:26,030 --> 00:19:28,380
It really broke my heart saying goodbye.

238
00:19:28,380 --> 00:19:29,620
Quit talking like you know it all!

239
00:19:29,620 --> 00:19:32,170
Hey, I'm telling the truth here.

240
00:19:32,170 --> 00:19:37,020
Sayaka said you weren't a bad option either.

241
00:19:37,560 --> 00:19:43,400
And what do you know? It was a success.

242
00:19:44,250 --> 00:19:48,050
All's well that ends well, right?

243
00:19:54,730 --> 00:19:57,400
Quit acting like you've summarized anything.

244
00:20:00,530 --> 00:20:05,480
You must've felt so relieved
when I told you I wanted to date Sayaka.

245
00:20:06,060 --> 00:20:09,630
How could you attend the wedding
with a straight face?

246
00:20:09,630 --> 00:20:15,190
You used to date the bride, for god's sake.

247
00:20:15,190 --> 00:20:17,540
What're you getting so heated for?

248
00:20:18,680 --> 00:20:21,180
You think you're so innocent yourself?

249
00:20:22,850 --> 00:20:25,450
I know you're no better.

250
00:20:31,780 --> 00:20:33,650
Don't even try to lump us together.

251
00:20:35,770 --> 00:20:40,700
I'm glad Sayaka didn't marry
a scumbag like you.

252
00:20:46,860 --> 00:20:50,100
<i>I thought Makoto was a dear friend of mine.</i>

253
00:20:50,100 --> 00:20:54,180
<i>Since when did his personality
get so twisted?</i>

254
00:20:54,850 --> 00:20:59,070
<i>He used to be such a good guy.</i>

255
00:20:59,070 --> 00:21:01,370
<i>Good people. Bad people.</i>

256
00:21:01,370 --> 00:21:07,050
<i>You can't judge a person's true nature
if you only have two extremes.</i>

257
00:21:09,330 --> 00:21:14,980
<i>I am nothing like Makoto.</i>

258
00:21:22,670 --> 00:21:25,180
<i>Sayaka is my wife.</i>

259
00:21:25,840 --> 00:21:31,940
<i>I'm the only one who can protect her.</i>

260
00:21:51,170 --> 00:21:52,660
Sayaka.

261
00:22:00,840 --> 00:22:05,400
<i>I love Sayaka.</i>

262
00:22:06,700 --> 00:22:12,050
<i>I'll be the one to make her happy.</i>

263
00:22:22,510 --> 00:22:26,470
<i>A drug that turns liquids blue.</i>

264
00:22:26,470 --> 00:22:27,560
[Kazuomi Hayashida]

265
00:22:27,560 --> 00:22:31,550
<i>Okay, let's say Sayaka was drugged
with a sleeping pill.</i>

266
00:22:31,550 --> 00:22:32,510
We're ready.

267
00:22:32,510 --> 00:22:37,680
<i>It's possible to acquire such a pill
if Sayaka was diagnosed with insomnia.</i>

268
00:22:37,680 --> 00:22:42,810
<i>But why use a drug
that would turn any liquid blue?</i>

269
00:22:42,810 --> 00:22:48,110
<i>Were they unaware of other,
non-color changing sleeping pills?</i>

270
00:22:48,110 --> 00:22:55,930
<i>Or was the one thing they acquired,
this color-changing drug?</i>

271
00:22:56,440 --> 00:22:59,510
<i>In order to disguise this change in color,</i>

272
00:22:59,510 --> 00:23:05,790
<i>the culprit would have to know
blue champagne was on the menu.</i>

273
00:23:05,790 --> 00:23:07,270
[Concerto]

274
00:23:07,270 --> 00:23:12,130
<i>Someone like the bride's mother,
Kaori Wakamatsu, for example.</i>
